A NOTE ON RUMSFELD v FAIR AND THE LEGAL ACADEMY
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EPDAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EPDAC_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Supreme Court\rquote s 8-0 decision (Justice Alito not participating) in 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Rumsfeld v Forum for Academic & Institutional Rights, Inc. (FAIR)
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F1332214522_ID0EXDAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F1332214522_ID0EXDAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F1332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
1
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 was neither momentous nor unexpected (a decision the other way would have been both). Its chief interest lies in the participation of the legal professoriat in the litigation. The suit was in effect an academic project, from which we can learn some things about the faculties of today\rquote s law schools, especially elite law schools like Harvard and Yale.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EGEAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EGEAC_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The background to the suit was the policy of the armed forces of not permitting homosexuals to serve. The policy is firm,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F2332214522_ID0EPEAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F2332214522_ID0EPEAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F2332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
2
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 but leeway in its administration is created by uncertainty as to what precisely is meant by saying that someone is a \u8220\'3fhomosexual\u8221\'3f--is it a matter of preference or orientation, on the one hand, or behavior on the other? It is that ambiguity that enabled the Defense Department in 1993, in a compromise with President Clinton, who had attempted to end the ban outright, to adopt its \u8220\'3fdon\rquote t ask, don\rquote t tell\u8221\'3f directive. The directive provides that homosexual orientation is not a bar to service unless manifested by homosexual \u8220\'3fconduct,\u8221\'3f 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100400_48_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100400_48_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*48
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 broadly and somewhat oddly defined as a homosexual act, a 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
statement
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 that the person is homosexual, or a marriage or attempted marriage to someone of the same sex.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F3332214522_ID0EBFAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F3332214522_ID0EBFAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F3332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
3
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 So military recruiters no longer ask applicants for military service what their sexual orientation is, but members of the armed forces who disclose their homosexual orientation are to be discharged.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EKFAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EKFAC_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
So there is discrimination against homosexuals in the military (though not outright exclusion), and the response of most law schools, beginning in the 1970s, has been to deny the Judge Advocate General\rquote s Corps (plural--each service has its own JAG corps) the same assistance in recruiting law students that the schools\rquote  career-placement offices provide to law firms and other potential employers who promise, as the JAG corps cannot, not to discriminate against applicants for employment on the basis of their sexual orientation. Not that the law schools single out JAG or other military recruiters. The denial of assistance applies to all employers who refuse to hire homosexuals. Nor are JAG recruiters (or other discriminators) banned from the law school campus. But they are denied the extensive assistance that the law schools offer recruiters who, so to speak, take the pledge. That assistance includes, as explained in the amicus curiae brief of the National Association for Law Placement, \u8220\'3fnotifying employers of the days or weeks set aside for interviewing \u8216\'3fseasons,\u8217\'3f inviting and accepting employers\rquote  requests to be included in the process, taking students\rquote  requests for interviews with particular employers, and scheduling the interviews at times that fit within students\rquote  and employers\rquote  needs .... Some schools provide teleconferencing or videoconferencing services to facilitate long-distance interviewing .... Other schools may even go so far as to provide lodging at the school\rquote s own expense for recruiters who travel from other cities.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F4332214522_ID0EQGAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F4332214522_ID0EQGAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F4332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
4
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 There is much more: for example, \u8220\'3fmany schools have recurring \u8216\'3fmeet the employer nights,\u8217\'3f or gatherings on campus at which students and employers\rquote  representatives can meet in a cordial, low-pressure, event that is more like a cocktail reception than an interview or meeting.\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F5332214522_ID0E4GAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F5332214522_ID0E4GAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F5332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
5
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EEHAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EEHAC_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100400_49_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100400_49_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*49
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 All this largesse is denied to military recruiters and other employers who do not promise not to discriminate against homosexuals. The law schools are discriminating against such recruiters.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EXHAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EXHAC_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Congress\rquote s response to this discrimination is a law known as the Solomon Amendment, which in its present form
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F6332214522_ID0E4HAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F6332214522_ID0E4HAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F6332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
6
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 provides that if any part of an institution of higher education (thus including a university\rquote s law school) prevents military recruiters \u8220\'3ffrom gaining access to campuses, or access to students ... on campuses, for purposes of military recruiting in a manner that is at least equal in quality and scope to the access to campuses and to students that is provided to any other employer,\u8221\'3f the entire institution is denied federal funding.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F7332214522_ID0ENIAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F7332214522_ID0ENIAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F7332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
7
}}}
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EUIAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EUIAC_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The law schools reluctantly complied, lest their universities lose federal funding. But a liberal lawyer named Joshua Rosenkranz, formerly head of the Brennan Center for Justice at New York University, organized the Forum for Academic and Institutional Rights, a coalition of law schools and law professors, to challenge the constitutionality of the Solomon Amendment. FAIR sought an injunction against its enforcement, lost in the district court, won in the court of appeals,
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F8332214522_ID0EAJAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F8332214522_ID0EAJAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F8332214522_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
8
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and lost again in the Supreme Court. FAIR\rquote s argument was that the Solomon Amendment imposes an unconstitutional condition on the receipt of federal funds: to obtain such funding a law school must in effect mute its opposition to discrimination against homosexuals by providing the same hospitality to military recruiters that it extends to employers who pledge not to discriminate.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EMJAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EMJAC_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A number of amicus curiae briefs were submitted. One of these, filed on behalf of a large number of Harvard Law School professors, opposed the government on a different ground from FAIR\rquote s: namely, that there is no violation of the Solomon Amendment as long as the law school, rather than singling out military recruiters, denies placement assistance to all employers who refuse to promise not to discriminate against homosexuals. The brief actually argues 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
against
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 holding the Solomon Amendment unconstitutional, because the professors\rquote  \u8220\'3fconcern, first and foremost, is in furthering the eradication of invidious discrimination. Accordingly, we are deeply 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_100400_50_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_100400_50_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*50
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 concerned about an opinion that would accept the assertion that the Solomon Amendment requires nothing more than equal access--but then conclude that the statute is nonetheless unconstitutional because it infringes upon associational rights, compels unwilling speech, or restricts expressive conduct.\u8221\'3f For \u8220\'3fsuch an approach could encourage attempts by discriminatory employers, educational institutions or other groups to evade compliance with various pieces of federal civil rights legislation ... by asserting that granting equal treatment without regard to race or sex would send a \u8216\'3fmessage\u8217\'3f with which they disagree.\u8221\'3f
}
